deck_excerpt: Ready to fly! Get hit by 5000 attack!
deck_description:
Incomplete rough draft of a deck made for Domain Format. https://discord.gg/Mb4NP7A8E5

The DeckMaster is Rocket Arrow Express 
It is important to know of the restrictions of this deck:

Rocket Arrow Express has the following restrictions:

  • Cannot Set cards
  • Cannot Activate Effect
  • Can only be summoned on an empty board

This obviously sounds really bad. However we can get around these restictions by doing the following things:

  • Only using Spells before summoning Rocket Arrow Express
  • Using Inherent Summons, and only using them for their Atk/Def points rather than effects

By doing this, we are rewarded by the ablity to have a "free" 5k attacking body on the field every turn. There is a finite amount of removal avalible to each opponent, this amy give you a good chance to win on its own.
The strategy is of course, to summon Rocket Arrow Express, use an inherent summon to summon out other beefy bodies, then wham our opponent. Simple!

 

As noted, this deck is incomplete. I need to find out what exactly it means to gain advantage using this deck, and there are many pieces which are not yet fully connected. 
For examples:

  • Red Arrows does not yet have an extra deck monster of my own to blink out
  • Blooming of the Darkest Rose while I don't yet have plant monsters
  • Time Escaper while I don't yet have Psychics

Here are some things I am activly trying to improve:

  • Need helpful Normal Summon
  • More Machine monsters to turn on Machina Ruinforce 
  • More plants/insects for Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown 
  • Find ways to search out Machina Ruinforce or Carnot the Eternal Machine 
  • Find ways to search out and use Bunny Ear Enthusiast without leaving a card on field. 
  • More Boardwipes (so the name of the deck works)

Important cards to know:

  • Machina Ruinforce is the biggest body in the main deck and can be summoned by banishing a total of 12 levels from GY
  • Carnot the Eternal Machine is the easiest inherent summon in the deck, granted you can send him to GY. Synergizes with Rocket Arrow Express which disallows him from activating his negative effect
  • Bunny Ear Enthusiast can blink out one monster temporarily, so we have an empty board for Rocket Arrow Express without needing to lose that monster permantly

This deck is a very close version of my HERO deck in Master Duel, I have adjusted it to be according to TCG Master Rules such as only having 1 call by the grave and instead of having only 2 fusion destinys there are 3 fusion destinys.

The template I used for this deck to adjust to was from @SinonSAO, so thank you to him for making this process significantly faster.

The difference between this deck and the template I used was that I replaced a good amount of the handtraps/staples with things like Destiny Draw and Draw hand mainly because of gas and thus this would make the deck more consitent overall. Plus, Draw Hand can actually be used for targets for destruction such as DPE + Just a quick favorite contact material just in case if you want to save your GY material for Wake Up + Gas for card advantage.

Another thing I've changed about this deck is I've put in a couple mini combos into the deck unlike Sinon such as Evil Hero Package for Board Destruction. Another mini combo you might have noticed is Elemental Hero Gaia being the deck, this is because this is an appilicable target for Infernal Rage to target for a special summon and this can also make dealing with big boss monsters somewhat easier which is good and by taking advantage of the infernal rage effect, infernal rage wouldn't be such a waste on the field considering the fact that Favorite Contact targets in the GY/Banished as well!

Last things I've changed is removing 1 Hero Lives for 1 E call instead. This is because in my opinion, it doesn't seem very nessecary to run 3 Hero Lives since you would be putting your life points are a very low 1000 Life Points which makes you very suspectable to things like small burn damage or small battle damage. At least, when you have 2000 life points, something like Sword Soul Strategist isn't gonna end the game for you. Another reason why I put 1 E call is mainly because of bait, this can be used as bait for things like ash blossom and E call isn't a once per turn either which prob doesn't matter due to having only 1 E call in the deck anyway. Sometimes, having heros in the hand can be better than having them on the field because of things like shadow mist being an appilcable target for discard effects like Faris or Forbidden Droplet.

Overall, this is a somewhat unique take on the HERO Archtype, but this works suprisingly well in Master Duel and although the deck is slightly different in the TCG, I have no doubts that this will work just as good, or even better than the digital counterpart. Also the reason why I made this deck is because I used to be a HERO player before SinonSAO took over the Hero Archtype, so I just wanted to have this as a take. Anyway, if I ever were to restore my HERO Deck, this would be a likely profile for the reconstruction of something so great that I have lost.

Thanks for hearing me yap, watch out SinonSAO, HEROS can come back for me, maybe not today, but some day it will.

-Kingsameri

deck_excerpt: Tenpai but it can go first :0
deck_description:
This build of Tenpai includes two separate "Going First" lines in the extra deck as well as 22 non-engine cards including both board breakers and hand traps. Tenpai in the OCG has strong matchups with Fire Kings, Snake-Eyes, Tear, Kashtira, and Voiceless, but it can struggle against certain tier 2 strategies, namely Labrynth, Melodius, and (especially) Runick. As far as control goes; this build is slightly less strong (due to no Lightning Storm) against Raika Traptrix but that deck is relatively untested and uncommon. 

You can replace some of the handtraps with more engine if that is a concern. Including Golden Sarc + Blaster is another one-card starter and it can technically make going first or second simpler. I strongly dislike having to run garnets in my main deck, but Blaster himself can sometimes be an extender for the link-climb going first combo. If you want more starters, cut the Effect Veilers and run Sarc + Blaster + 1 more copy of Thrust. You can also run Santa Claws in the Veiler slots, if Kaiju are more your speed for board breaking. The interesting thing with Santa Claws is that it isn't HOTP, so you can break basically a whole board with multiple copies in hand. It's a bit of a meta call, but the Kaiju path is valid as well.

Fadora is much more important in this build of the deck; it is the core extender that allows the going 1st combos to function, but it is also a huge breakpoint for Imperm or other monster negation. It is very searchable and is a brick on its own, so we are still only running 1. There is an argument to run 2 for more consistency, but 3 copies is too many.

An issue with choosing to go first as classic Tenpai is that the deck can struggle to get rolling without Zhongdora's effect to special summon from deck. The strength of this build's extra deck is not that we will be choosing to go first in game 1, but that we can strongly go first in games 2 and 3. OTK decks like Tenpai will always have an advantage in game 1, so we just need to shore up the weakness to the side deck that classically harms going second strategies.

N.s = Normal summon

S.s = Special Summon

Unfortunately, our going first strategies are pretty limited to two card combos. Fortunately, any combination of two engine names is full combo. As many of the two card AFD lines become similar I won't list every two card combo, but there is some variance depending on your extenders. Usually you want to summon Bident Dragon before AFD, but if Fadora starts the combo in hand it is usually better to go into AFD first.

  • Baidora + Fadora in hand (Ends on Crystal Wing + Heavenly Spheres)

N.s Baidora -> Set Brimming Sangen Manor -> Activate and use field spell to add Zhongdora -> S.s Zhongdora from hand -> Synch 7 for Ancient Fairy Dragon -> AFD effect to gain LP and add When There's A Will There's A Way Out -> AFD effect to S.s Fadora in hand -> Fadora effect to S.s Zhongdora from GY -> Synch 7 for Bident -> Bident effect to S.s any name from GY -> S.s Ultimaya Tzolkin -> Set WTAWTAWO (lol) -> Tzolkin effect to S.s Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon -> Link off Tzolkin + Extra name from Bident to make Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres

  • Baidora + Fadora in hand (Ends on Black-Winged Assault Dragon + Heavenly Spheres)

N.s Baidora -> Set Brimming Sangen Manor -> Activate and use field spell to add Zhongdora -> S.s Zhongdora from hand -> Synch 7 for Ancient Fairy Dragon -> AFD effect to gain LP and add When There's A Will There's A Way Out -> AFD effect to S.s Fadora in hand -> Fadora effect to S.s Zhongdora from GY -> Synch 7 for Bident -> Bident effect to S.s any name from GY -> S.s Ultimaya Tzolkin -> Set WTAWTAWO (lol) -> Tzolkin effect to S.s Black-Winged Dragon -> Contact Synch for Black-Winged Assault Dragon by banishing BWD on field and Bident from GY -> Link off Tzolkin + Extra name from Bident to make Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres

Read my last deck-list for full OTK through Prosperity combo guides.

deck_excerpt: With the pack "Return of the King", Red Dragon Archfiend's competitive power-ups have finally reached Masterduel!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
Hello King/Queen, you've come to the right place to make use of your new Jack Atlas cards! With the pack "Return of the King", Red Dragon Archfiend's competitive power-ups have finally reached Masterduel! Red Dragon Archfiend has 12 one card combos, and many additional ways to two-card combo, making the deck extremely consistent - on par with other synchro strategies like Swordsoul and Mannadium. This allows the strategy to fit in A TON of non-engine cards and still be playable! As a result, this deck can confidently play through minor handtraps like Ash Blossom and Impermanence. High impact handtraps such as Nibiru and Droll can be shrugged off as well!
 
If you want a more detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, please check out my earlier article on Red Dragon Archfiend from last year. 
 
GLHF Duelists!

This is an adaptive rogue deck that attempts to use the extenders from the Goblin Archetype to have easier access to monsters, as opposed to the commonly used BA engine. The main decks leads down a line with

3 level 3s -> Cherubini. Cheribuni send Cloak. Last level 3 and Cherubini makes Bardiche. Bardiche Send Torn Scales, Set RUM Force. Banish Cloak, search Stained Greaves, chain Torned Scales to summon off banish, chain Staiend greaves to summon off torn scales summons. Or Search boots off cloak for more spell and trap search. Make break sword, Bardiche pops break sword, make dark rebellion. Pass, with access to bardiche pop and requiem negate next turn at the least.

The Side Decks contains a mix-up play to go into Utopia double Via Stained Greaves and Shade, then make utopia kaiser to summon number 11, set RUM Launch, and make Kali Yuga on the opponent's turn.

Hope you have as much with this deck as I am! Goblin Biker Big Gabonga is fun to say.

Okay, we all know how expensive that genus loci build is. Like, sheesh, I remember when aromaseraphy jasmine was $2 a pop. Do you want to play a more tame version of plants, with a nice smooth number of 40 cards in the main deck? here you are!!

For those unfamiliar, here's the most basic combo line for this deck.

Summon Aromalilith, special Laurel from deck, link into jasmine, Laurel gains 500, jasmine search Lily. Lily special summon self, send whatever you used to get it, search the field spell, activate field spell, search regulus. Jasmine tribute Lily, get smol jasmine. Regulus summon himself because he's so cool. Jasmine+Jasmine into link 3, search Aroma Blend, aroma blend fetch humid winds, pay 1k, search Marjoram, gain 500 from winds, Link 3 summon marjoram. Congrats, grave removal and regulus negate in 1 card. Now imagine what you can do with the other 4!
Seto Kaiba Deck V1
Yami Bakura Deck V1

Now, some people may say that Purrely is the better deck. To that, I say... Uh.. Shut up. Nerd. I don't have any banned cards >:)

Alright, Obedience School goes into 3 melffies, go into forest, forest searches melffy tag. Tag revives detached melffy, make forest again, search emlffy playhouse, bam, a compulsory. 

Rescue Cat goes into verifawn and mine mole. That's a naturia beast and a card draw, bucko

That's all the basic lines. Everything else is pretty much built around puppy getting kalantosa, and pinny mixing with other cards to make desert locust, and then either baronne or tenyi from the extra deck, depending on what's pn the field.

Ninjas are a really fun archetype in modern Yugioh. They can go toe to toe with most decks.

In the side deck I added a few tech choices as well as some handtraps you might like more than what I've already included in the deck.

Yellow Dragon Ninja, Upstart Golden Ninja, Karakuri 7749 and/or 339 can be swapped with White Dragon Ninja and/or Twilight Ninja based on personal preference. If you bring in Upstart Golden Ninja you might want to add the extra dancing leaves for an extra potential hand trap in your hand to use his effect.

The video I added from FafNir covers a ton of Yugioh content and is conveniently segmented so you can pick the areas you want to learn about specifically.

Ninjas have a pretty high skill ceiling, and, some would argue, skill floor. I think the floor is kinda low with tons of room to master the deck.

I recommend reading all the cards closely since there are a number of Ninja special summon effects that work differently from the vast majority of Yugioh special summon effects.

GLHF!

deck_excerpt: Upper plat- lower Diamond Ghoti Deck
deck_description:
Ghoti Deck 

Because of Ghoti I designed this deck with less cringe and more board breakers since that is what Ghoti is about. It's still very limited but for those who enjoy playing this archetype want to see how far it can get competitively here is a decent list. You can fill this deck with more hand traps over consistency cards but I prefer the latter. I think HT are a bad mechanic in ygo but feel free to do whatever this is just how I think would be the most fun and competitive list out there. there obviously are some HT because you have to run them rn but i think inf imperm is the best one for the main deck

This magikey deck focus a bit more on a slow paced game rather than comboing infinitly, there are still some good negates and you can establish a good board just not an OTK unless if you run Utopia Double but we all know that money doesn't grow on trees.

Side deck is just other good staples/preferences but I am most likely gonna stick with the main deck list.

deck_name: An actually competent Ghostrick deck in 2024
deck_excerpt: I’m back from the dungeon to bring more jank! (It’s kinda competent this time tho)
deck_description:
I've been waiting for good Ghostrick support since the decks conception, and Konami has continued to disappoint every single time. So, I took matters into my own hands, and made this abomination. Ghostrick surprisingly has a decent bit of really powerful spells and traps, and this list takes full advantage of that by playing a crap ton of them. You only really need the 4 Ghostrick monsters, as if you know how to maneuver your cards right, (and you get hella lucky) you can sometimes just straight up run out of space on the board. One thing that could be capitalized off of is obviously the ability to make UFD, which would require you to play a level 3 engine, but I wanted to keep this as pure as possible. S:p is actually kind of a bad card in this deck, just because it clogs up your emz, but if you get it to resolve it doesn't really matter. I am very open to suggestions as to how to make this better, as I probably don't have the best ratios for this deck.

Ghostrick shot is actually crazy in this deck, as it gets you Ghostrick monsters on the board without having to waste your set, and shot late game (if you ever get there) actually gives you a way to loop allucard, which provided your board stays in tact, allows you to have an infinite Amount of searches. This leads to basically having every Ghostrick power spell/trap always at your disposal, but this is hard to do if your opponent has, you know, INTERACTION. Alot of the things you do will be on your turn, but just because of the nature of flip monsters you do a lot of your setup on the opponents turn. I highly advise just trying the deck out, you'll see how much potential it really has, and I hope people actually try and innovate on it. That's all from me, but anyway... GHOSTRICK BEST DECK LETS GOOO!

deck_excerpt: IT'S JUDGMENT TIME FOR MASTERDUEL LADDER!
deck_description:
The Dogmatika Spellbook deck has been re-made and updated with the newest cards and meta specific counters for the March 2024 Masterduel metagame!
 
This version of Dogmatika is augmented by Spellbook cards, providing for insane advantage while summoning Jowgen during the endphase! After resolving Spellbook of Judgment and Alba Zoa's effect, you effectively FTK your opponent as most of their extra deck is in the GY and Jowgen prevents any special summoning! Your follow-up for next turn is often a 5-7 card hand full of Spellbooks and Dogmatika cards, since Spellbook of Judgment + Dogmatika gather incredible amounts of resources every turn.
 
Being a "rogue" and relatively unknown deck, Spellbook Dogmatika isn't to be underestimated - it can fight toe to toe with the strongest decks on Masterduel! Put your x3 Spellbook structure deck to competitive use!

If you want a thorough guide on this deck, check out my article from last year by clicking here.

deck_excerpt: Use politics to your advantage and summon Slifer for huge damage!
deck_description:
Join the Domain Format discord server for information on rules and deckbuilding: https://discord.gg/Q9G3Md5pMf

A "group hug" deck is a kind of deck that wants to give resources to your opponents in order to gain their trust in table politics, then win the game after it's been reduced to a 1v1. This deck uses Two-for-One Team to draw cards, summon Slifer from the hand, or send cards from the deck to the grave depending on what we ask from our opponents. The plan is to team up with someone and help them take out the other players, or be a mediator and help out whoever's currently losing. The Poker Knights help us get 3 tributes for Slifer and also search him if we have Thunderspeed Summon or Joker's Wild aswell. Arcana Triumph Joker and Utopia Double are our backup win conditions. If we can set up Appropriate and Infinite Cards together, we could have a 20+ card hand and a incredibly strong Slifer on the field.

Get some Ojamas on the field, use Creature Swap or Creature Seizure (which only allows the user to choose a normal monster; hence why this deck only uses the normal-monster Ojamas), and use your opponents monsters and/or Enraged Battle Ox to destroy them. Super Polymerization can be used to take the Ojamas you just swapped with your opponent along with Ojamas on your side of the field to summon Ojama King and/or Ojama Knight. Use Land of the Ojamas (Skill Card) so you don't have to have Ojama Country in your main deck to swap the atk/def of monsters on the field. Note that Enraged Battle Ox gives piercing battle damage to all Beast, Beast-Warrior, and Winged-Beast monsters you control, so it accomplishes what Fairy Meteor Crush does, but Fairy Meteor Crush is still included just in case. You could easily switch it out for any equip card or beatstick that you desire to increase the damage dealt. Enchanting Fitting Room is used to help get the Ojamas on the field. You could also take out one Creature Seizure and/or one Creature Swap to add other cards that might make this deck more consistent/powerful. Also note that Polymerization can be used in place of Super Polymerization since Super Polymerization is expensive and Polymerization should do the job since you'd likely have all 3 Ojamas in your hand and/or on your side of the field at some point.

What cool monsters you have, would be a shame if I used them for my fusion monsters.

Armed Dragon Thunder deck with minimal non-engine. The main deck is focused around the level up line, with a few auxiliary cards with varying utility like Pile Armed Dragon (whose usability I am debating), the Rulers (supporting the 7-axis) and Armed Dragon LV10 White, Dragunity Arma Gram (supporting the 10-axis).

Regarding the alternatives, like showcased in MBT's Ruler deck a package with Dragunity Guisarme, the small rose dragons, potentially Dragunity Remus, opens access to synchros. Lightning, Dragon Ruler of Drafts could be a good idea and triggers the thunders but doesn't support the main line while using resources from the hand. Black Metal Dragon can be a normal into Striker Dragon to add Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon but it maybe bloats the amount of normal summons in the deck. Armed Dragon, the Armored Dragon is indeed a card, Wynn the Wind Channeler can search the small ones but locks your effects, Nowru Aries the Vernal Dragon is a neat Ruler-like choice as a one-of, Sacred Sword of Seven Stars is decent if the 7-axis is much more emphasized. A Neos engine with Neos Fusion to get out Armed Neos and from there float into the other big ones is... a choice, and due to the variety of levels in the deck there's a variety of other xyz one could use, like the Full-Armored Xyz package.

deck_excerpt: Branded Despia  / Salerno WCQ Regional Top 4
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Carmine Olivieri

Tournament: Salerno WCQ Regional – March 17th 2024

Placement: Top 4

This could very well be my last deck on here (don't quote me on that) since I'm done buying Yu-Gi-Oh aside from support cards that have positive applications in my current decks. Example: I will be buying the new Ice Barriers when they release because Gorgeous George makes Revealer a level 10 synchro summon; I will not be buying the new Trickstars because they have no negates, and no deck can stand without negates. That's why I combo'd them with Generaiders, who have negates, and so your opponent actually gets punished for all those cards you give them. It even lets us use otherwise unused Generaiders Naglfar, to protect Lycoris, and Frodi, so your opponent can decide to draw and burn or let their monsters die unavenged. The ideal is to get Holly Angel on the field to protect Lycoris before you commit her, which is why I've maxed on Corobane and Lilybell is at 2. You need that Crimson Heart. I was just barely able to make it and draw a second lvl 9 Generaider for Vala on my last game, which saved me. The other interactions are very well-known or covered in my other Generaider deck.

I wanted to post this here so it's available for people to toy with, but mostly so I don't have to keep digging for an old screenshot of it. Have fun, and in case I don't see you, good afternoon, good evening, and good night.

Here's my Competitive Build of the Timelord Deck ! This Going Second Deck got a lot of differents patterns you can use in order to OTK / FTK your Opponent ! The Plays are so weird but so creatives too !

FTK (if you got the ressources) :

- Any Timelord + Eldlich / Kaiju Slumber / Carnot (if you get Ash'd or Veiler) = Gustav Max . Use Gustav to Burn. Then Overlay for Liebe + Liebe Effect. THEN if you got any Exodius, you can shuffle the Monsters from the GY back to the Deck and Extra Deck, Special Summon Exodius + Eldlich / Carnot = Gustav Max. Use Gustav Max to Burn... If you have the ressources to keep going, just REPEAT the Loop 2 times more and you're going to FTK your Opponent. (Also Note that you can use Zaphion as a Link material for Bujinki to go +1 and an instant XYZ Summon).

OTK's :

- Any Timelord + Kaiju Slumber + Triple Tactics Talents = OTK . (Put Jizukiru on your field, go for TTT, taking control of the other Kaijus, it will send him to the GY, then you can go for Gustav Max, Eff for Burn (2000) THEN Liebe, Eff for 6000 ATK, then go to the Battle Phase for Game.

- Limiter Removal activated on Liebe during the Damage Step is an Instant OTK.

- Limiter Removal x 2 activated on Jizukiru or Carnot during the Damage Step is an instant OTK.

- Double Edged Sword (Equipped on a 2000 ATK Opponent's Monster) + Raphion is an instant OTK. (Opponent takes 4000 Battle Damage in Battle Phase, THEN Raphion Eff in End of Battle Phase to Burn for 4000 Damage).

- Double Edged Sword (Equipped to a 2000 ATK Opponent's Monster) + Any Timelord & Exodius / Time Maiden is an OTK (Opponent Takes 4000 Battle Damage in Battle Phase, THEN Attack with Exodius or Time Maiden for 4000 Battle Damage).

- Michion + Sandaion is an OTK . (Michion HALVES LP in Battle Phase + Sandaion Burns for 2000. THEN go for Gustav Max, Eff to OTK.

BONUS :

- If you got 2 Shifters and any Exodius in hand, you can use the first Shifter Turn 0, then Special Summon Exodius by Recycling the first Shifter, in order to use the second Shifter for Turn 3.

- Spooky Dogwood can either make your Opponent passes Turn (Then you can OTK him) or trick your Opponent into going for a full special summon Turn (THEN you can go for the XYZ Tarentula and OTK him. 

- When Exodius Attacks, it can Foolish Any monster from your Hand or Deck, you can send Carnot or Eldlich for XYZ Summons in Main Phase 2. (Or you can send Time Maiden if you need more ressources in the Grave.

- Astral Kuriboh protects your XYZ Tarentula from any Destruction Effects or Battle (which is Broken since it works as a Material).

- Sauravis Protects your monsters from any interruptions.

- Tokusano Shinkyojin + Zaphion (While on the Field) is a DRAW 3. (Tokusano makes you Draw 2 & Zaphion sent in the Grave makes you Draw 1)

- You can also play Dark Ruler No More in this Deck, since Michion HALVES LP (That does not count as Burn Damage).

- You can also play Yubel in this Deck (Strong Interactions with Double Edged Sword & Timelords).

 

PROS :

- When you don't Brick, the amount of combos is insane and the Plays are very creative.

- Can OTK EZ

- Got 2 Cards OTKs

- Can Play Under Shifter / Nib / Droll

- Can Play Shifter & Nibiru too

- Can win games with Spooky Dogwood during TIME.

- Plays Exodius, which can recycle Kaijus from the GY to give more ressources for Kaiju Slumber.

CONS :

- Too Bricky

- Loses to Nibiru sometimes if you go too crazy lol.

- Loses to your own Spoky Dogwood / Piri Reis lol.

- Loses to Shifter if you touch your Tokusano Shinkyojin / Foolish Burial / Eldlich as Starting Hand. 

- Exodius can RUIN your VARIANCE when recycling your monsters from the Grave.

 

NOTE :

(This version is a Shifter Version. It does not include a go First Side. If i get enough comments about this DeckList i'll upload another version with a Going First Side).

If you got any Spicy / Tech Cards / Combos that would fit the Deck, let me know, i'm always working on ways to make this Deck even more competitive.

    Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio: The Normal Summon of the deck. Starter of the engine, which will special summon the next card;
    Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra: The garnet. Special Summoned by Scorpio's effect, it will then search for a "Polymerization or "Fusion" spell. The target is of course a copy of Relinquished Fusion
    Predaplant Verte Anaconda: Sometimes you just eat handtraps for breakfast, or you're up against someone that actually reads and realizes Cobra is a serious choke point. So? Just make Verte
    Starving Venom Fusion Dragon, Predaplant Dragostapelia, and Predaplant Triphyoverutum: The occasional payoff, which is great, considering the deck's innate lack of use for the Extra Deck. You have a lot of room for Predaplant boss monsters, of which these 3 are the most generic of the bunch

deck_description: Blazing Arena is a Selection Pack, released on March 29th, 2024. In this selection pack, many new support cards have been updated for master duel. I will review the combo decks supported in this pack. And I'll start with the Battlin' Boxer. Below is the deckprofile for everyone's reference.
for fun

Backup for my Swordsoul deck in Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel.

External engine / package:

  • Tenyi
    Tenyi Spirit - Adhara: Small, yet important. You can't completely cut this one out, yet you don't want to see this one too often either. This card helps you access the odd-level Synchro Monsters of the deck, since all Swordsoul monsters are even-leveled monsters
    Tenyi Spirit - Shthana: Niche spot removal. It triggers from the GY, a place where your opponent rarely checks. Also, it's one of those Tenyi that gets overlooked-- until it pops something
    Tenyi Spirit - Ashuna: A very strong Ash bait. If it goes off, you get a free Tenyi on board. If not, it doesn't really hurt your main combo lines. Mainly, you want to recover this one with Adhara's effect, or the next card;
    Tenyi Spirit - Vishuda: Spot removal that doesn't destroy rarely comes packaged in a Level 7 DARK easily searchable Main Deck monster. Vishuda just happen to be one of those exceptions
    Heavenly Dragon Circle: Your relief escape against anything that targets a Wyrm. If you have a Swordsoul Token, its secondary effect will be live, which can extend your plays with another Tenyi

    Monk of the Tenyi: Tenyi monsters are live in the hand and/or GY. They don't do anything on the field. This card is the middleman for that job specifically
    Shaman of the Tenyi: A reborn of any Wyrm is a welcome addition. Now you have a backup plan in case your main line Swordsouls are destroyed
    Draco Berserker of the Tenyi: Sometimes you want to hit hard, but your Swordsouls don't hit hard enough? Enter Draco Berserker. It pairs very well with Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying, making one round of effect resolution a clean +3 in card economy

  • Yang Zing
    Denglong, First of the Yang Zing: This card's first effect will never go live on an engine this small. However, its second effect can dump any Wyrm to the GY. This opens up tons of options based on the game state
    Yazi, Evil of the Yang Zing: The definition of a drive-thru card. Summon him, pop himself, and get any Wyrm of your choice from the Deck, fuss-free
    Baxia, Brightness of the Yang Zing: Mass-spin on summon. For a Level 8 Synchro, this guy has poor stats, so if he can't beat over anything left after the initial effect, use the 2nd effect to pop himself and get a Level 4 Swordsoul back on the field
    Chaofeng, Phantom of the Yang Zing: Supposedly the strongest Yang Zing monster the game had to offer. While the effects are strong, it's pretty niche unless you destroy something with it. The floodgate effect can be considered offline since this deck doesn't run Main Deck Yang Zing monsters

Note: The Yang Zing line is a RARE occurence. The deck's main lineup and its augmentary Tenyi cards are often already strong enough to win you most of your games. However, Yang Zing cards pack some of the most powerful Wyrm support effects in the game, which makes them hard to overlook

Yes, there were some bricks from both sides, but despite that, this deck shows that it has the means to turn a corner and get the ball rolling. deck_name: Master Duel - Beetrooper Battlewasp Combo Tutorial
deck_excerpt: ygoprodeck.com, yugipedia.com, yugioh.fandom.com, yugiohtopdecks.com, ygorganization.com, rushcard.io, discordapp.com/discord.gg, imgur.com
deck_description:
The Yugioh Combo Tutorial Type Insect Deck that is Anti-Mainstream, combining The Beetrooper Archetype with The Battlewasp Archetype in Master Duel, with a Duel Review of 3 different Duel Play Strategies, which can be Implemented and can be Improvised during The Duel. And also The Deck is Arrangement in The March 2024 Master Duel Banlist format.

 

  • First Strategy
    The First Strategy is to Link Summon Giant Beetrooper Invincible Atlas then sacrifice it to Special Summon Beetrooper Sting Lancer to Add Beetrooper Landing which is a Fusion Spell Card for Beetroopers and use that Spell Card to Fusion Summon Beetrooper Cruel Saturnas which has The Effect of Add The Beetrooper Card then take The Heavy Beetrooper Mighty Neptune then Special Summon Beargram, Shelled Emperor of the Forest Crown by Banishing 3 Insects including the Giant Beetrooper Invincible Atlas from The Grave after that The Effect of The Beetrooper Cruel Saturnas will be active and Special Summon again the Giant Beetrooper Invincible Atlas to The Field and then Return The 3 Banished Insects to The Deck to Special Summon The Heavy Beetrooper Mighty Neptune.

 

  • Second Strategy
    The Second Strategy is to Link Summon a Giant Beetrooper Invincible Atlas then activate The Effect by Tribute 1 Monster Insect to Special Summon 1 Beetrooper Monster from the Main Deck then Special Summon The Beetrooper Sting Lancer and activate The Effect to Add Beetrooper Landing and Fusion Summon Ultra Beetrooper Absolute Hercules to The Field. This strategy is useful for beating enemy monsters whose Attack is below 4000 and for avoiding The Effects of The Opponent's Cards until The End of Our Next Turn, and if The Ultra Beetrooper Absolute Hercules Attacks, at The End of The Battle Phase you can Special Summon an Insect monster with an Attack of 3000 or less from The Graveyard, It's pretty good to be able to Special Summon again The Giant Beetrooper Invincible Atlas from Grave to The Field.

 

  • Third Strategy
    And for The Third Strategy, I tried to combine The Synchro from Battlewasp with The Link which is Seraphim Papillion to Special Summon Battlewasp - Sting the Poison on The Opponent's Turn, to anticipate if there is an Effect from The Opponent's Monster so that it can be Negated by Battlewasp - Sting the Poison with tribute an Insect Monster. Then combine it again with XYZ from Number 3: Cicada King, to Negate The Effect of The Opponent's Monster and also to Special Summon an Insect Monster from The Hand or from The Graveyard.

 

Note: Those are The 3 Strategies for this Example of an Insect Type Deck, which I call The BeeWasp Deck. And the following is the arrangement and what cards are used in this deck, both the arrangement of monsters and what spell cards and trap cards are used in this BeeWasp Deck, with the number of cards used in The Main Deck totaling 45 Cards and 15 Cards in The Extra Deck.

Well, that's all for now Guys, if you have Suggestions and Constructive Criticism for This Tutorial, please write them in the comments, that's all from me, I hope this tutorial can help Duelists, especially Beginners or Noobies who want to make variations of Decks that are not the same as before, aka which is not mainstream, and The Term is not a Meta Deck with a High Tier and High Budget.

deck_name: my magnet warrior battle city deck

deck_description: bystial engine + galaxy photon 41 cards all gas no handtraps in main

Isolde is now banned, now wat do? we play next best girl Amazoness war chief. She can take on multiple men at once, and probably not only in a fight, but also something that includes joining bodies as she set poly directly from deck. Problem is she locks you into attacking with amazoness. Not that big of a deal breaker since we can special summon her using raijin or double hooking on opp turn then fusion summon on our turn.

Our plan going 1st is just gonna be summon raijin using warchief or cadet and something, set double hooking. Pass. On our opp end phase if raijin is destroyed he will summon back warchief and cadet or something and both gives you search to poly and feast for follow up.

This is a basic earthbound deck. They, or this deck specifically, are go 2nd deck with some easy way to get several medium-large monster fast. Ultra poly is our harmonic synchro fusion at home. We play 1 HSF to at least Here is some simple combo with them.

- Combo 1: starts with ground keeper and stone sweeper.

Discard stone sweeper, search line walker, normal line walker, search prison, activate prison, normal ground keeper, ground keeper eff summon stone sweeper from deck/gy. Alternatively you can normal ground keeper special line walker, search prison, activate prison special stone sweeper.

Synchro summon geo gryphon using stone sweeper and ground keeper, gryphon eff special stone sweeper, synchro summon geo gremlin.

This set up will let us have disruption using geo gremlin. And we can special ground keeper using gryphon quick-eff, thus summon line walker thus search harmonic synchro fusion to help us OTK

- Combo 2: starts with ground keeper, stone sweeper,

same thing as above until we get all 3 earthbound prisoner monster. Activate ultra poly, fusion summon geo kraken using ground keeper and stone sweeper. Activate ultra poly gy eff to special ground keeper and stone sweeper. Synchro summon muddy mudragon. After that you can go either synchro summon hot red dragon archfiend abyss or use muddy mudragon eff to fusion summon grapha.

- combo 3: starts with ground keeper and garbage lord (or other lv5 DARK extender like kaiser vorse raider).

normal ground keeper, special line walker, search HSF. Special garbage lord. Synchro summon muddy mudragon. Activate HSF sending line walker and muddy mudragon special abyss and grapha.

deck_excerpt: Believe it or not, Raye can still fight toe-to-toe with the top meta contenders in Masterduel, especially when backed with boardwipes!
deck_description:
Not only does Raye have a manga adaptation, Masterduel's 25th Anniversary Animation video gives her an animation as well!

The manga has basically already concluded, Sky Striker anime soon Konami? (pwetty plssssss IT WOULD BE SO GOOD!)

Believe it or not, Raye can still fight toe-to-toe with the top meta contenders in Masterduel, especially when backed with an incredible arsenal of blind-second field wipes such as Evenly Matched, Triple Tactics Talent and Change of Heart! Nuke the board, surgically eliminate your opponent's card and outgrind them in a game of resources!

The philosophy with Blind Second Sky Strikers is to wipe out most if not all of your opponent's resources that they slap down on the board going first, and then close out the match with Sky Striker's unparalleled grind game.

This deck has cards specifically picked out for the March 2024 Masterduel meta, like Triple Tactics Talents/Thrust (super good since duelists often monster effects during your turn or handtraps you) and 7 monster stealing cards (particularly good at cracking Snake-Eye boards).

The current meta allows for Evenly Matched and Raigeki to obliterate most duelist's boards this format since they spend all their resources building their "unbreakable" board only to fall to 1-2 cards - allowing your Sky Striker gameplan to go off unhindered and out-resource your opponent.

If your weakened opponent hasn't surrendered yet due to the sheer resource advantage and offensive pressure this deck generates, you can clear the board with a plethora of cards including Linkage, allowing Raye to OTK all by herself!

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

GLHF Duelists!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Let’s play with some Reptiles and their evolutions!
Deckmaster: Evoltile Megachirella 
Domain Restriction: FIRE // REPTILE // DINOSAUR // DRAGON

Main Combos
Turn 1: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-58977149
Turn 2: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-58977281 
50% of the deck blatently stolen from NamedElemental . Check out their deck here: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/domain-reptpile-448123 
Deck writeup written by me.

Category Breakdown

Recursion Engine:

Keurse, the Ogdoadic Light, Undaunted Bumpkin Beast, Reptilianne Nyami, Miscellaneousaurus, I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species-     

Dinosaur Package:

Miscellaneousaurus, Dinowrestler Pankratops, Dinowrestler Martial Ampelo, Souleating Oviraptor, Petiteranodon     

Deckmaster summons:

Xeno Meteorus, Evolsaur Diplo, Evolsaur Lios, Evolsaur Vulcano     

Card Acess:

Viper's Grudge, Ogdoadic Daybreak, Nunu, the Ogdoadic Remnant, Black Mamba, Aron, the Ogdoadic King, Foolish Burial, Snake Rain       

This overall, is a deck that plays from the graveyard, ultilizing it’s ability to natively resummon key pieces of advantage generating monsters.

The strength of such a strategy is to outlast our opponents and eventually set up a state where our deck regains so much more per turn than our opponents, winning the war through attrition

First let’s examine the deckmaster: Evoltile Megachirella 

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? 

- Turn 1 combo
- Refill XYZ materials
- Provide Ability to discard
- Access Dinosaur Engine
- Provide Spell/Trap destruction on demand

Our deckmaster is surprisingly more versions than at first glance may seem. The ability to not only start our plays but continue to be extremely valuable through the entire game allows us to feel like we have 1 more card in our hand at all times. 

An underrated part of the deckmaster is access to Evolsaur Diplo, who destroys spells and traps on summon. Use this to destroy problematic floodgates or advantage without. In addition, once Evolsaur Diplo is shuffled back into deck by our recursion pieces, we can do this once again.
The refill of XYZ material allows us to revive powerful XYZ monsters from the grave without losing access to their effects.
Many of our cards, like Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark  only have effects in GY, so allowing ability to discard is great

In a deck like this, a deckmaster like Evoltile Megachirella provides extremely valuable consistency and deck functionality

What do we want our dinosaurs to do? 

- big monster (Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus)
- Search Field Spells ( Horned Saurus )
- Pop/neutralize monsters
- Lasting staying power

Dinosaurs are the second aspect of evolution for reptiles, and as such are much stronger and scarier. Our cards like Ultimate Conductor Tyranno can neutralize boards, Dinowrestler Pankratops can remove threats, and Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus becomes a pain for our opponents to remove. The fantastic aspect of this deck is its ability to access all of this through Misc

As I’m sure you’ve noticed, we only have one Miscellaneousaurus. BUT we can access it multiple times using Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark returning Miscellaneousaurus to GY! As we continue to use Miscellaneousaurus, we increase the arsenal of things it can access, and thus gets more powerful

The combos are here:

Using Misc for baby, then NS Deckmaster for Xeno:
[Banish 2]: Summon Petiteranodon who can be destroyed by using our Deckmaster to summon Xeno Meteorus 

Using Misc for Dinowrestler to access Pank:
[Banish 1]: Summon Dinowrestler Martial Ampelo who can search Dinowrestler Pankratops 

Using Misc for Extra Deck plays (after reshuffling key pieces of combo):
[Banish 4]: Summon Evolsaur Lios or Kaitoptera to summon Evolzar Lars or Horned Saurus respectivly

Example Combo for Turn 2 return Miscellaneousaurus to GY:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=889807-58977281   


The endboard:

- Ultimate Conductor Tyranno
- Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll 
- Evolzar Lars 
- Lv8 XYZ

Good beatstick, steak beat sticks, opponent beat sticks cannot activate, refill beat sticks


What do we want our Recursion to look like?

- Resummon Ogdoadics
- Refill xyz materials ( Evoltile Megachirella )
- I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species-
- Resummon Reptilianne Nyami and Undaunted Bumpkin Beast 

This aspect here is the core of the deck. Every time we resummon Nauya, the Ogdoadic Remnant by Keurse, the Ogdoadic Light , we can add an Ogododic Spell or Trap. Each time we resummon Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark , we can another opportunity to use Miscellaneousaurus. I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- gets out of control very quickly, and given the amount of powerful field spell, likely happens quite frequently. Our free summons will continue until time ends, and through that, we make sure we always end up ahead on turn rotation.


What to recycle?

We may find the opportunity through Pot of Benevolence , Slash Draw , or Jar of Avarice to return cards to deck. 

This is a powerful effect that allows us to use our deckmaster combos once more. Here is a list of combinations to consider:

  • Evolsaur Lios + Evo-Singularity (access through Miscellaneousaurus or Deckmaster Evoltile Megachirella)
  • Dinowrestler Pankratops + Dinowrestler Martial Ampelo (Use Miscellaneousaurus to access)
  • Evolsaur Diplo (Spell/Trap destruction accessed through Evoltile Megachirella)
  • Souleating Oviraptor  + Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju / Ultimate Conductor Tyranno 

Notably, many of these combos rely on Miscellaneousaurus and involve Dinos. Make sure to confirm you have enough Dino resources to use Miscellaneousaurus after recycling resources back 

By recycling Evolsaur Diplo , you change your recycle spell into additionally allowing you to destroy a S/T for the LP cost of normal summoning your deckmaster and a discard.

Strange Stand-alone cards

These cards may seem off at first glance, but they have a reason for existing

  • Polymerization 
    Searchable through Kaitoptera and summons Horned Saurus 
  • Volcanic Queen
    Searchable through Infernal Flame Banshee 
  • Pot of Benevolence and Soul Release
    Targets down opposing recursion engines
  • Alien Stealthbuster, I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- 
    Searchable through Nauya, the Ogdoadic Remnant, and the plethora of reptile GY senders, in addition to "A" Cell Recombination Device and Mysterious Triangle 
  • Frostosaurus
    The garnet nessisary for Xeno Meteorus to summon Transcendosaurus Glaciasaurus 
  • Foolish Burial and Peaceful Burial
    Access to reptiles in the case that our combo is unsucessful
  • Spright Sprind
    Sends Undaunted Bumpkin Beast or Reptilianne Nyami, which are recurring free summons from GY
    Can be made using tokens from Ogdoadic Daybreak or a link-2
  • Pitknight Earlie
    Great card that is hard to fully remove from the field due to resummon when due by battle or card effect 
  • Reptilianne Melusine
    Made using Reptilianne Coatl, a searchable reptile monster
  • Shadow's Light
    summons Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark or Reptilianne Melusine 

 

Foolish Burial targets list:

  • I.A.S. -Invasive Alien Species- 
  • Nunu, the Ogdoadic Remnant 
  • Night Sword Serpent 
  • Reptilianne Nyami 
  • Undaunted Bumpkin Beast 

 

Other considerations:
Infernal Flame Banshee, Evolzar Dolkka, Number 60: Dugares the Timeless, Galaxy Photon Dragon, Lavalval Chain, Planet Pollutant Virus, Bystial Magnamhut, The Tyrant Neptune, Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy, Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames, Card of Safe Return, Reptilianne Ramifications, Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring         

Please Enjoy the Beauty of Evolution and the rest of your day!

A fun pure T.G. deck with more meta options in the side deck.

This is my attempt to cook an Earthbound Prisoner deck without using Runick cards. They're objectively good and everything, I just hate them. The deck has a beat and you can dance to it. You'll likely sack some people at locals with this build but I don't think it's topping a regional any time soon. Needs some love and optimizing. 

You can pretty easily Baronne by summon 5 and end on 2 or 3 synchros + Flamberge and Formula Synchron in the S/T. Have fun!
dragons go brrr

Springans Explanation

What's Springans?

Springans is an archetype introduced in Blazing Vortex, that continued gaining support until 2023, with Photon Hypernova, that put a stop to the Albaz Lore (For now, 31/03/2024), and stopped the Springans Supports too. The deck actually saw Competitive play when Cyber-Stein was free, being an FTK deck that was actually consistent and budget. After the Cyber-Stein ban, the deck fall down into the rogue/for fun category, only seeing results at locals. Even tho the deck is not competitive, it's still playable, and with a lot of potential, as new archetypes still comes out that in one way or another, synergizes with the deck.
Now that we covered the history of the deck, we can go deeper, into the Positive and Negative points of the deck.

 

Positive Points

  1. Price
    The deck is very very cheap. The only card that actually costs something is Gigantic "Champion" Sargas, but that card is so busted that you can use it in other decks (We'll talk about it later). The deck core is around 15/20 bucks (At the moment obv), so it's very budget, and a lot of expensive card that you see in a lot of decklist can be actually cutted or changed for some budget variants (Like S:P Little Knight or Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis).
  2. Cards
    The archetype cards are pretty strange. They can go from garbage to busted, with no mediocre cards. For example, all the spell cards in the deck are so broken, like Springans Watch (A searcher and a foolish, all-in-one) and Tally-ho! Springans (Up to 3 monster reborn and a searcher, all-in-one).  Some monsters are good too, like the already mentioned Gigantic "Champion" Sargas, a card that's so good that other decks played it for a lot of reason: Piece of interruption during Opponent Turn, Searcher of Therion cards, a generic rank-up for a Zeus with 4 material (A thing that was possible only in rank 1/2/3/5/6 deck or in specific decks).
  3. Engines
    The coolest part of the archetype, in my opinion, is the engines that you can play with it. A lot of rank 4 in the game are generic, meaning that you can use ANY level 4 monster to summon them. Considering that the deck can summon a lot of Level 4 monster even without the normal summon, so, as long as an XYZ monster has a search effect, this allows the deck to make a lot of combos with various engines, like: Exosisters, Utopia, Time Thief, Centurion, Snake-Eyes, Etc... 
  4. Flex Spots
    Considering that the deck plays like 20/25 cards (Based on the ratio that you use), you can put anything in the deck having a low risk of bricking (Handtrap, Going Second cards, Extenders, Etc...). Obviously, if you play other engines, the flex spots will change.
  5. FTK
    The deck is literally made for this kind of stuff. As long as there's an Xyz monster that searches, the deck can do basically anything, like putting insane boards or even locking the opponent. The risk is the consistency of the deck, obviously reduced by the number of combo pieces in the deck, but you know the drill: High Risk, High Rewards. 
  6. Engine in other decks
    As I alredy mentioned when talking about Gigantic "Champion" Sargas, every deck that can put 2 level 4 monster on board can play this card, but if you want, you can even play a little Springans engine in the deck, that basically make 2 level 4 monster you control becomes 2 level 4 monster AND 2 Xyz monster (Both not Number, so they can be used not only for link plays, but for F0 too). For example, a deck that use this engine is Crystal Beast.

 

Negative Points

  1. Handtraps
    Unless you're playing a lot of extenders or ways to dodge Handtraps, like Crossout Designator, the deck is very weak against Handtraps. Even tho the "softer" handtraps, like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring or Effect Veiler, are not that much of a deal (If you have the right hand or some extenders), the "strongest" handtraps, like Droll & Lock Bird or Dimension Shifter, are a big red STOP for all the plays. Even tho cards like Dimension Shifter are used only in specific deck, Droll & Lock Bird or Nibiru, the Primal Being are instead used in a lot of decks/side decks. 
  2. Going Second
    Unless you're not playing specific going second cards, going second with this deck is basically impossible. Considering that the main card of the deck is a Field Spell, that can be stopped with a single Mystical Space Typhoon, the deck can't go second that easily, even with the best hand you can ever imagine. Useless to say that the deck is weak against all the lock or floodgates.
  3. Monsters
    I know, that's strange, considering that in the Positive Points, I specified the strenght of the archetype cards, but there's one big flaw. The archetype monsters (The main deck ones). They all sucks. Their effects are not that good and a lot of them are pretty specific or kinda meh. The only good part of those cards is the effect that overlays them, the rest of the effect is 90% of the time mediocre at best. Just saying that one of the best main deck monster in the deck is Springans Kitt, that's basically a branded card and has nothing to do with the Springans cards. 
  4. Brick
    The deck is actually pretty solid, so bricking will happen like 1 time in 10 hands, but when you brick, you can't do nothing. While other deck can still go to back up plans in case of bricking, when this deck bricks, the only thing you can do is a T set and pass (That's a 99% lose signal). That's way I like to play lots of extenders of searches, depending on the version I'm using.
     

  

Meta

In the current meta, the deck as like 0% of being meta. Considering that the meta decks nowadays all revolves around 1/2 card combos with absurd grinding and 15 minimun handtraps (Watch Voiceless Voice or Snake-Eyes) or Floodgates/Anti Meta Strategy (Like Yubel). On top of this, all the top handtraps of the formats are deadly for the deck. We hope that the banlist can treat as good or that Konami releases new supports for the deck or cards that work very good with it.

 

The List

The list that I created for this decklist is a generic pure one with some extenders and handtraps, but you can change it based on your likings. I will still give you some advice about the ratio of the cards, if you want to play more cards without going with a 60 card list: 

  • Monster:
    • Springans Rockey: 3x 
      He's the star of the deck. Rockey+The field spell is full combo in all the lists. No less than 3.
    • Springans Brothers : 2x
      Brothers is that card that is too heavy at 3x but too weak at 1x. 2x is the best ratio imo. 
    • Springans Branga: 2/1x
      If you play the pure version, always go for the 2x. Good searcher, you always need that extra copy. If you're playing a spicy version, go for the 1x. Considering that you're playing other engines, 2x can be heavy, unless you're playing a Rank 8 deck, in that case, stick with the 2x.
    • Springans Kitt: 3/2x
      Same thing as Branga. In the pure, go for 3x, in the other versions, go for the 2x.
    • Springans Captain Sargas: 1x
      It doesn't matter the version, Sargas in hand is always a brick and you want it in your deck. Always go for the 1x.
    • Springans Pedor: 0x
      The worst Springans. The effect is not that good, and having 1 extra discard for the Field Spell is not that necessary, considering all the searchers in the deck and the other good target to discard.
    • Supreme Sovereign Serpent of Golgonda: 0x
      This card was actually very good in the first version of the deck, when all the new cards didn't exists. Nowadays it's just a brick or a wasted slot. But, I wanna give him an actual use. If you're playing a rank 8 version of the deck (With Therion or Horus), it's a free extenders and a discard fodder, considering that he can summon himself back from the Graveyard.
  • Spell:
    • Actually, except for the continuos spell, Springans Booty, all the other spells are so busted that you need to play 3x. Booty, in the other hand, is a Field Spell Searcher that cannot be ashed or belle, so 3/2x, it's good both ways.
  • Trap:
    • The opposite of the spell part. All the trap sucks, except for Springans Blast!, that's a monster negate if you control a Springans Monster. It can be meh in the wrong hand, so put it in 1x, if you want.
  • Extra Monster:
    • Springans Merrymaker: 2x
      Even tho the monster is very good and the combo starter of the deck, 3x is not that necessary, considering that you can recycle it with Springans Rockey. 2x Is the best ratio.
    • Springans Ship - Exblowrer: 1x
      This monster is actually pretty good, but not that good to put it in 2/3x. It's effect is actually cool, basically a destruction that target the zones and not the cards, but is not that broken and in some match-up destroying is not the best option (Look at Unchained). Still a good target.
    • Gigantic "Champion" Sargas: 2x
      I already talked about this card before, but I will explain quickly why it's that strong. This card does everything. Firstly, it's a searcher that doesn't need any setup (I'm looking at you, Springans Branga), that can search not only Springans, but Therion too, making Therion "King" Regulus easier to search without using cards like Qliphort Genius. Secondly, it's a free destruction/bounce in the opponent turn, that actually work very well with the other Springans Captain Sargas. Third, It's a way to add more material to Zeus, a card that's not only very strong, but that in Springans is much stronger, considering that you can setup an 8 materials Zeus without using 100 steps combo or some strange ways. The only reason why we don't play 3x, is because the deck doesn't need it. Trust me, if a game is so pushed that you need the third copy, it's better giving up than playing that game (Experience talk).
    • Sprind the Irondash Dragon: 1x
      I mean, you only need it to activate Branded in High Spirits and to summmon Springans Captain Sargas from the deck during the End Phase. More than 1 is useless.

That's all for the ratio, now, let's talk about all the possible budget changes in the deck.

 

Changes

(Before you start reading, those cards are expensive nowadays, 31/03/2024)

Now, considering that the deck is not that expensive, there are few cards that you actually need to change to make it budget:

  • Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder: Considering that Zeus is basically a Springans card (In the spirit at least), changing it it's a real challenge. You can go with the Evilswarm Exciton Knight, but considering that Zeus is a staple in a lot of decks, paying 10 bucks for it is not that big of a deal in my opinion. Who am I tho to judge you? Do what you want with your money.
  • S:P Little Knight: Go for Knightmare Phoenix.
  • Underworld Goddess of the Closed World: Actually, you don't need it in the main deck. You can just put some Kaijus in the side deck and it will be okay.
  • Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess: Apo is not that easy to change, considering that she's the only real good link -4 monster boss monster with disruption. Another one link -4 monster that can change her is Unchained Abomination, that actually synergizes very well with the 2 Sargas. 
  • Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis: Typhon is actually pretty good in the deck because a lot of end board monster we use doesn't have 3000+ ATK, but he's not that important for the deck. Just put any extra deck monster that you want.  

 

Engines

As I already tell, Springans can be fused with a lot of other engines, and sometimes those fusions are actually really good. So, I'm giving you 3 options that, always in my opinion, are worth a shot:

  • "Synchron"
    Now, as Synchron I don't mean the 1948302 step combos that ends with God himself on the board, but playing just 1 of 2 cards, that are either Assault Synchron (For Baronne plays) or Revolution Synchron (For Ancient Fairy Dragon combos). Either way, they're both good, and they don't require a lot of space in the deck/extra deck, unless you don't wanna go for the ftk line, but that's your choice. 
  • Centurion
    This version is probably one of my favorite. Centurion synergizes so well with the archetype, being both a starter for the deck, in case of bricking, and as an end board combo. Probably, one of the best version to include in the deck.
  • Snake-Eyes
    This is a strange duo actually. Thanks to Infernal Flame Banshee, the deck can basically add any Snake-Eyes monster, without using the normal summon and with some link material left on the board. There isn't an actually synergy between the 2 deck, but Snake-Eyes is so op, that just searching an archetype monster, can basically bring you an absolute disgusting board. 
     

 

Combos

Actually, the combos the I use nowadays are the same that I used times ago in an old list, so I will just post the link here:
https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/springans-pure-post-phhy-324130
The list is a bit different, but the combos are basically the same. If you want to know more insane combos, you can just search online. There are a lot of psychos out there trying things that even God didn't know.

 

Konami Support

Now, after reading all the wall text, you noticed that the deck is not in a very good shape nowadays. The only way to make things better is with a new banlist or with new Supports, but I doubt this will happen. The only thing that can actually go out of the banlist that can help the deck, is probably the Zoodiac cards, while Cyber-Stein will probably remain banned, unless they make an errata, and at that point, the card will be probably useless. For the supports, I think Konami said stop with the Albaz lore or, if they print something new, it will be just for Branded or some useless lore card. Never stop believing tho. 

Ending 

 I hope you will try the deck and start loving it, just like me. Thanks to you all for the reading. Bye bye.

deck_excerpt: Ashened Harmonic Synchro Fusion Earthbound Servant
deck_description:
This deck aims to make use of my recent obsession Harmonic Synchro Fusion alongside the Ashened monsters (Pre-LEDE support).
Thanks to the Ashened only needing their normal summon when Obsidim, the Ashened City isn't available and Earthbound Prisoner Stone Sweeper being able to special summon itself when a card is on the Field Zone, you can spend your Normal Summon on Earthbound Prisoner Line Walker in order to get Harmonic Synchro Fusion.
The main idea before commiting to the Synchro and the Fusion is to use Assault Synchron and Priestess of the Ashened City to make Muddy Mudragon who will give you access to Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss & Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World when you use HSF.
Some issues in this deck in particular include the fact that we don't have many great Fusion options when compared to the Synchros and that Awakening of Veidos locks you out of ED plays, except for Infernal Flame Banshee and Garunix Eternity, Hyang of the Fire Kings.

 

The side deck options here and a sort of plan B and instead of doing anything with HSF, you instead use the Owner's Seal effect of Ashened for Eternity on Veidos and target it with World Legacy Monstrosity in order to make Laevatein, Generaider Boss of Shadows.

Hopefully the next wave of Ashened support helps this particular brew a little, and if not.....i guess i'll just play Ashened Runick.

deck_excerpt: Runick Naturia  / Waterford WCQ Regional Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Patty

Tournament: Waterford WCQ Regional – March 30th 2024

Placement: Top 8

deck_excerpt: Destroy your way to Masters 1 with the Dogs of Destruction!
deck_description:
The unchained demon dogs of destruction have finally arrived in Masterduel with its support from the newest selection pack, Blazing Arena! 
 
The three new Unchained monsters Yama (Search Unchained monster + special summon Unchained from hand/GY), Sharvara (Special summon + set Unchained S/T from deck), and Shyama (summon itself from GY + destroy S/T) increases the strategy's consistency and raises it's strength to such powerful levels that the deck can now sport 15+ staples and achieve full combo while comfortably playing through interruption! The deck's main combo now ends on 6+ interruptions with only 1 card (Normal summon Tour Guide anyone?) and has many two card combinations that end on the same board state. 
 
This power boost enables the deck to play toe-to-toe with Masterduel meta heavyweights such as Snake-Eyes, Kashtira and Labrynth. With this new support, this strategy can now destroy its way to the top of ladder! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
  
UNCHAINED is best played pure, so naturally the deck core is large but also made as compact as possible to accommodate staples. In total, the Unchained and its supporting cards compose of 21 cards in the maindeck. A small Tour Guide package is played with 1 Fiendish Rhino Warrior as its target to achieve this deck's 1 card combo. The garnets meant to be summoned from deck are at 1 (Rhino Warrior, Unchained Soul of Disaster, Shyama, and Abominable Unchained Soul). Starters are played at three, since you want to draw into them to initiate your combo (Tour Guide, Abomination's Prison, Aruha, Sharvara and Escape). 
 
The rest of the deck is composed of STAPLES. 
 
The standard Maxx C package (3 Ash, 3 Maxx C, 2 Called By and 1 Crossout) is included so that you can come out on top of the Maxx C minigame. If you get Maxx C'd as an Unchained player, you'd have to abruptly stop your turn since this deck doesn't really play into the annoying cockroach very well. Nibiru  and Imperm are included as a Crossout targets, since this deck sometimes loses to those handtraps.
 
A Triple Tactics Thrust package (3 Thrust, 1 Imperm, 1 Talents) is included into the deck, since it meshes very well with the strategy. You can either grab a staple like Talents, Imperm or Prosperity from the deck, or you can directly set an Unchained Spell/Trap to further your plays.
 
42 cards are used rather than 40 since it lowers the chance of drawing into this deck's several garnets. 
 
Pot of Prosperity also makes this deck very consistent since you excavate for 6 very comfortably, despite the two extra cards. My usual Prosperity banish targets are Knightmare Phoenix, Muckraker, Underworld Goddess, D/D/D Deus Machinex, Zeus and either of the Knightmare monsters. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Unchained's gameplan is to establish as much interruption as possible (usually in the form of destruction or linking away opponent's special summoned monsters) and out-resourcing/OTKing your opponent. The deck functions as a control combo deck that generates lots of resources while also whittling down your opponent's with many interruptions. When ahead, this deck can finish off your opponent very quickly as it clears the boards with multiple destruction effects, linking away your opponent's monsters and swarming the field with several high attack monsters. 
 
Going first, you generally set up a 4-6 interruption board. When it is your turn again in turn 3, you can OTK with the board presence, monster removal and the many resources you have amassed. 
 
Going second, you weaken your opponent with handtraps and boardbreakers so you can turn the gamestate into one where you can OTK your opponent. To clear your opponent's board, you have Unchained Soul of Disaster and Anguish's linking away your opponent's board. If you have extra link material, Unchained Abomination can also destroy cards multiple times. If you cannot OTK your opponent from that position, you go for a control centered playstyle where you set up your interruption-based board and out-resource your opponent. 
 
Here are the combos for Unchained:
 
1 CARD COMBO 6+ INTERRUPTIONS - Tour Guide of the Underworld =  Unchained Soul of Rage (Link away opponent's special summoned monster -> Knightmare Unicorn Shuffle) + Rakea (Destroy card to summon from deck Abominable Unchained Soul to destroy 1 card) + Escape of the Unchained (Destroy 1 Unchained and 1 card opponent controls) + D/D/D Wave High King Caesar (2 summon effect negate/destroy, detaching Sharvara sets from deck Unchained S/T)
  1. Normal summon Tour Guide. Activate her effect to summon Fiendish Rhino Warrior from deck. 
  2. Link summon Unchained Soul Lord of Yama using Tour Guide + Rhino Warrior. 
  3. CL1 Yama to search for Unchained Twins - Aruha from deck, CL2 Rhino Warrior to send Unchained Soul of Sharvara to GY. 
  4. Sharvara's effect triggers to set Escape of the Unchained from deck. 
  5. Activate Aruha's effect to summon himself by destroying Escape. 
  6. Escape activates to summon from deck Unchained Twins - Sarama.
  7. Activate Sarama's effect to set Escape from the GY and destroy Aruha. 
  8. Aruha activates to summon from deck Unchained Soul of Shyama. 
  9. Link summon Unchained Soul of Rage using Yama + Shyama. 
  10. Activate Shyama's GY effect to summon from GY by targeting Sarama to destroy him. 
  11. CL1 Yama to summon from GY Sharvara, CL2 Sarama summon from deck Rakea. 
  12. XYZ summon D/D/D Wave High King Caesar using Shyama + Sharvara. 
  13. Set any additional spells/traps. 
2 CARD COMBO 5+ INTERRUPTIONS - Unchained Soul of Sharvara + Any Unchained S/T =  Unchained Soul of Rage (Link away opponent's special summoned monster -> Knightmare Unicorn Shuffle) + Rakea (Destroy card to summon from deck Abominable Unchained Soul to destroy 1 card) + D/D/D Wave High King Caesar (2 summon effect negate/destroy, detaching Sharvara sets from deck Unchained S/T)
  1. Set Unchained S/T. 
  2. Activate Sharvara's effect in hand to summon itself, destroying the Unchained S/T. 
  3. Unchained S/T summons from deck Shyama. 
  4. Link summon Unchained Soul of Yama using Sharvara + Shyama. 
  5. CL1 Yama to search for Aruha from deck, CL2 Sharvara to set Unchained S/T from deck (With another name from the one you previously activated). 
  6. Activate Aruha's effect to summon himself by destroying Unchained S/T. 
  7. Escape activates to summon from deck Unchained Twins - Sarama.
  8. Activate Sarama's effect to set Unchained S/T from the GY and destroy Aruha. 
  9. Aruha activates to summon from deck Unchained Soul of Disaster. 
  10. Link summon Unchained Soul of Rage using Yama + Soul of Disaster. 
  11. Activate Shyama's GY effect to summon from GY by targeting Sarama to destroy him. 
  12. CL1 Yama to summon from GY Sharvara, CL2 Sarama summon from deck Rakea. 
  13. XYZ summon D/D/D Wave High King Caesar using Shyama + Sharvara. 
  14. Set any additional spells/traps. 
Other two-three card combos are not as optimal. Remember if you don't have Tourguide or the above listed combination of Unchained cards, or your combo is interrupted by a well timed handtrap, your usual goal in Unchained is to make Yama -> Unchained Soul of Rage -> Summon two level 6s -> summon D/D/D Caesar -> Set Unchained Traps. 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Targeting negation/interruption is usually not effective with this deck, since Sharvara and Rakea's quick effect all help dodge targeting! 
  • Be mindful and careful of Nibiru. This deck has no natural answer to it, so you'll have to play around it or play safe if you think it is in your opponent's hand. However, if your opponent neglects your D/D/D Wave High King Caesar, he can negate/destroy it. 
  • If you somehow draw into Fiendish Rhino Warrior, when you summon Tourguide summon from deck Rakea instead. Set your Unchained S/T from hand, then continue combo as usual. 
  • If you have all the pieces for full combo in hand, don't activate Abomination's Prison until after you searched with Unchained Soul of Yama when you combo so you can play around Droll & Lockbird (it's kind of rare in Masterduel anyways). 
  • During your opponent's turn and you're interrupting them with the standard board, try to detach Sharvara from D/D/D Wave High King Caesar first. Sharvara sets an Unchained S/T from deck. Use that freshly set S/T as Rakea's destroy target. This preserves your other Unchained traps like Escape and Chamber for use!
  • If you get Evenly Matched, you can dodge the effects easily if your standard board is set up! When Evenly is activated in CL1, CL2 Rakea targeting Unchained Soul of Rage to destroy, CL3 Unchained Escape targeting Rakea and another of your Unchained cards to destroy. After Rakea and Rage has been destroyed, banish everything leaving only D/D/D Wave High King Caesar on the field. CL1 Rakea to summon an Unchained from deck and CL2 Rage to recover from GY an Unchained card. This leaves your negates with Caesar intact while maintaining your resources in field/hand! 
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
The interactive playstyle and grindgame based gameplay with Unchained is really entertaining to me. I would describe the Unchained strategy as a combination of Sky Striker's link-centred grindgame, Dragonlink's resillient combo, and inherent boardbreaking ability of Exosisters! The compact and consistent deck core allows for a gazillion staple cards (kind of mandatory in Masterduel), a deck style that I've enjoyed since building Spright and Live Twins. 
 
Overall, Unchained is now a solid meta contender that is consistent and powerful deck that is able to carve out it's own niche in the meta due to being a combo deck that doesn't insta-lose to the likes of Droll & Lockbird. 

Destroy, destroy and destroy all the way to the top of Masterduel's leaderboards with the Unchained dogs of war!

GLHF Duelists!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Super consistent 3-axis deck that ends of multiple interruptions
deck_description:
Combo Tutorial Below

Phantom knights, the Crazy combo deck that no one is playing in Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel is still one of the most competent decks of 2024. It's resilient, consistent and most of all capable of going toe-to-toe with the meta. Especially now that Bystials are rarely seen. So today's combo tutorial, I'll be showing you your 5 basic combos to get you started!

Gameplay Footage below ⬇️

Ninjas are both one of the cheapest and most unique decks in Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel 2024. The deck excels at clogging your opponent's board by locking their monsters in Face-down defence position and then attacking direction via the effect of Meizan the Battle Ninja. Yes, Ninjas do struggle against backrow decks, but with Labrynth players taking a break due to Fire Format you're less likely to run into them. Even if you do, reply 2 showcases how you can handle them even when going second. On my last point, most of the cards needed from this deck can be obtained by the structure deck meaning that you won't need to spend on any pack opening. Just get 3 structure decks and you're mostly set to jump in Master Rank and start having fun!
